tip.text:
P. Franco is a bit of an institution on the low intervention wine scene - almost single handedly making 'natural' the coolest wine for Londoners to drink. By day it's a mighty friendly shop stocking unpretentious liquids - of varying price range. (France and Italy dominate the wine offerings but you can still expect a hefty selection of bottles here, from the USA to Australia.)

By night (four a week) it becomes one of the most intimate eating experiences about. Where guest chefs work their magic over two induction hobs and serve up all sorts of goodies to a large communal table. Though cooking styles change depending on who's in the kitchen, you can always expect high calibre grub from these guys - paired with intriguing natural wine selects. Our fave bit? The way beginners and wine geeks are welcomed with equally smiley faces.

Kitchen times:
Thurs: 6-9
Fri-Sat: 6-10
Sun: 2-9

Any mention of Clapton and bucket-loads of cool ensue, and that's exactly the case with Biddle Bros. Situated on the frontline of London gentrification behind the spot's original shop front - this joint is a breath of fresh air, despite the many questionable mustaches it's packed with. Expect jazz in the early evening, dj's spinning ambient bangers later on and spectacularly reasonable prices, not to mention you'll find the likes of Staropramen, and Boddingtons on tap.

It’s a shame you can’t drink in this craft haven, but you can certainly do some stocking up for the nuclear apocalypse. Maybe you know what a growler is, maybe you don’t - short story shorter it’s a big ‘ol vessel (just shy of 2l) to carry beer in. Well, they’ve got plenty growlers here and you can fill it up with your choice of 8 brews on tap. Counter pressure means beers stay fresh for 6 weeks!

The walls are absolutely packed with craft bottles, be they local or global, so don’t try telling us you couldn’t find anything you liked here. Locally produced gin, rum and vodka have all managed to find themselves stocked here. Much booze to be had.

This taqueria has all the spice of a real roadside joint without any of the bowel anxiety. Work your way through a veggie jackfruit taco, topped with crunchy sweet potato; or a taco packed with slow-cooked lamb topped with coriander and onions; and a steak quesadilla perhaps? It's important you know it wouldn't be weird to order one of every taco. No shame; be free, young warrior.

The drinks are just as cray as the colourful decor. Get off on lime, watermelon or cucumber margaritas (with your choice of tequila or mezcal) or try your hand at a 'Michelada', which is basically a beer-based Bloody Mary. Curious aren't you pussy cat?

Ps: It's £2 tacos on Tuesdays. Hells yeah.

listing.name: St John at Hackney Brewery x Ela
listing.subtitle: Beautiful Beer & Cypriot Kebabs

tip.text:
A brewery and food joint in a renovated railway arch might not have you rubbing your eyes in shock, but there's plenty more to this place than meets those eyes. Ostensibly, it's a brewery and taproom with a rotating kitchen out back, but the attention to detail here is quite a sight - from the way they make their beer in vats that would have Walter White raising his eyebrows, to the understated beauty of their huge window facade and the 200-year-old church pews that line the walls.

The result is a damn fine place to have a high quality beer (they have 11 lagers, ales and stouts on tap) and get full. It's also deeply rooted in the community, with heavy involvement in local projects in collab with the church of the same name.

Out back is a kitchen currently inhabited by Ela, creators of simple, incredibly tasty Cypriot food. Inspired by the 'world's best kebab shop' in Cyprus, their 'babs come in wondrously marinated chicken, pork or halloumi variations stuffed full of slaws, feta, currents and salads. Big enough to share, these are truly tasty bites. Add in a nice sun-trap garden and hefty speakers and you've got a suitable spot to kick back and let some nice times roll.

The Chesham Arms is really all you could want from a pub - an open fire, a well curated selection of bevs, a nice little balcony, and a huge garden out back with wooden benches for the squares and hay bales for the more whimsical punters.

The garden is a real afternoon sun trap, making the call of afterwork pints very hard to resist if you’re lucky/unlucky enough to have The Chesham lying in wait on your commute home. But, guilt aside, once you’ve plonked yourself on a hay bale, with one hand around a cold pint and the other patting some stranger's dog, you’ll start to think that going to the pub everyday isn’t so bad after all. And with Yard Sale Pizza a phone call away, there isn't actually a reason to ever leave. Ever.

Oslo is a no-chance-of-failure kind of place; a late night Hackney staple. Downstairs is a lively restaurant/bar where you can enjoy Nordic themed grub with interesting craft beers and well made cocktails. But this place is really about the upstairs - a music/gig/club/get-crunk space where you can carry the night on later than you really ought to. If you hit it really hard upstairs, there's a chicken shop bang opposite which (at 3am) glows like some kind of mirage in the night.

What was once a boozer with a dodgy rep on the Murder Mile has gradually earned its place in people's hearts as a loveable, slightly scruffy community hub with hella soul. There’s been no million-pound facelift here (or however much pub facelifts cost), instead, you’ll find a creaking tavern with plenty of nooks and crannies adorned in random vintage bits and bobs, worn floorboards, log fires and mismatched furniture.

This is a big pub with the intimacy and charm of a small one: where weekly comedy nights are legendary and a late Saturday night pitstop will be rewarded with an unpretentious raucous dance to Wham or suchlike. Add in one of the biggest beer gardens in East and you’ve got yourself all you require from a neighbourhood boozer.

The Cock Tavern is a real pub’s pub: where all the other pubs would go for a pint after work and talk about their pub-related woes. Scuffed hardwood floors, repurposed furniture and steamy window panes make for a seriously cosy experience inside, and for the summer months they boast ‘Hackney’s smallest pub garden!’ (Seriously ‘garden’ is a stretch).

As for the beers, they host regularly rotating guest ale slots that feature some of the best up and coming cask bevs from Hackney and beyond. And for food? You’re looking at simple pub fare - not the new school small, sharing plates thing, but Scotch eggs, sausage rolls, pork pies and the like, all done well. This is how we like our pubs, you should come here.

Remember that sexy menu at Peg + Patriot? Well we do. And so does Matt Whiley (aka The Talented Mr Fox) 'cause he put it together. He got a food waste shaped bee in his bonnet and decided to set up a cocktail bar that's all about reducing it. How? Using only sustainable ingredients, distilling, fermenting and brewing in an on-site 'lab' and waging war on straws.

You too can fight the good fight, in a more relaxed manner, by slurping on his seasonal cocktails. Think strawberry wine, lemon balm gin and whey, or the fresher carrot, hemp seed and liquorice. Soak it up with sourdough and homemade kohlrabi or pickled celeriac and truffle and you might as well be at a spa. Sort of.

Moth Club - short 'of course' for The Memorable Order of Tin Hats - is a wondrously kitsch time warp of a boozer and event space. It’s a glittery mash-up of two cultural scenes colliding: an ex-servicemen’s club whose members still shoot the shit and play darts in the old bar whilst a sprightly and unsightly blend of Hackney young’uns come and embrace a lil' joyous abandon.

Nice indie gigs, 80s nights, bingo, themed quizzes (Peep Show, Ru Paul, Simpsons...) and film screenings take place under the gold glittered ceiling, amid red velvet booths and the iconic red and black chequered floor. Yep it's got the aesthetic, but it's also got the kind of welcoming vibe that’ll have you spinning around to Abba at midnight without a care in the goddamn world.

What is it with Hackney and great pubs? Owned by Five Points Brewery, The Pembury Tavern is another absolute corker. The beer selection includes all theirs of course but there's plenty of other independent brews to be sunk - in cask, keg, can and bottle form.

Constantly crammed with young bearded types eating pizza, this boozer is also packing a pool table, a bar billiards table and stacks of board games - just incase getting boozy isn't enough to keep you occupied.

All the silver linings here with strong drinks, low lights and good times. This cosy, quaint and intimate little spot is located right around the corner from Hackney Empire and features your perfect East Laandan cocktail list, including a monthly rejig of the classic old fashioned.

Once you've chosen your poison from the witty (if a little try hard) menu, prepare to be impressed. We like a sherry heavy menu so went for the 'Sherry Woo Woo'. We're fully on board with making sherry cool again. Maybe that should be our new slogan.

Tucked under a railway arch in Hackney Central (obviously), you can find these vodka vultures distilling 'till their heart's content. It might look like a scene from Breaking Bad, but we can assure you there's no meth-laced vodka here.

These guys mean business; their vodka has been touted as some of the purest in Europe and what's great is that you can drink on-site from their neat little bar, followed by a game of ping pong.

This place is more than just a vodka distillery though, with plenty of events popping off. Plus if you're a vodka boff or simply want to know what you're putting in your body, vodka tours are available to book.

This boozer is a favourite with Clapton locals for its extensive beer selection, jazzed up pub grub, and - most importantly - its beer garden. It’s big, green, shady and sunny in appropriate amounts and full of Clapton’s finest chilling out on deck chairs. On a cold day you could do a lot worse than propping up the bar inside or nabbing one of the chesterfield sofas for a little tête-à-tête.

Food is seen to with tapas-style sharing bits like Padron peppers, chorizo croquettes and the like; Sunday roasts with a good veggie and vegan options; burgers and plenty of nawty desserts too.

They say location is everything (not sure who ‘they’ are but we’ll go with it) and this canal-side Clapton boozer would be our first piece of evidence if we had to defend that claim in court. Average food, typical Young’s beers and not the greatest service aren’t enough to deter us from a pint by the water after a stroll along the River Lea Navigation.

In summer there are all kinds of walker/biker types glowing with those post-exercise endorphins, whilst the winter punters tend to have the rosy glow of a winter stroll. Year round there is a general vibe of people who have just done a positive thing with their Sunday. It’s nice, just don't worry about the food.

Self proclaimed "friendly Hackney pub", this handsome Victorian boozer is run by Norwegians, and decorated with candlelit antiques, unique collectibles, and a moose head.

Go for foreign film nights, ladies nights, a competitive pub quiz, and a rock, paper, scissors night - you heard that correctly. You're sure to be involuntary signed up to whatever's going on by the staff, but you'll succumb to the idea when you realise how much fun they're all having. There is also a beer garden with blankets for you to snuggle up in if it's chilly. Cringe or just the right side of organised fun? Erm you guys take this one.

listing.name: Pub On The Park
listing.subtitle: Vibey Pub with a Huge Garden

tip.text:
Pub on the Park is an absolute classic in the area and there's several reasons for this. It's a lively spot right on London Fields, with outdoor decking overlooking the park. It also tends to show the big games on huge screens, and serves up plenty of savoury pub grub - think burgers, fish and chips, nachos, salads and more.

So it can get pretty chock-a' with other good-time folk like yourself. Good to know then that you can ask for your beer in a plastic cup and take it out onto the field. There's even a flood lit boules court to let the games carry on into the night.

OK we've seen the look on your face. How can a pub be 100% vegan, you're wondering. Well it pretty much means that, wherever possible, all the trimmings (food, drinks, fixtures and fittings) are plant-based and sustainably sourced.

Food is seen to by Club Mexicana which means tacos, nachos and burritos piled high with guacamole, tomatillo salsa, sour cream, pink onions, pickled chillies, chimichurri, fresh lime and coriander. Sounds tingly and tasty right? Our fave was the tofish sandwich which went down a treat. Wash all that down with cask ales (without the fish bits), Beavertown beer, small batch wines and some tasty cocky Ts.

We also popped by for brunch and devoured some tangy, spicy chick'n waffles with chilli maple and bacon (as decadent as it sounds); a full Mexican breakfast with all the plant-based trimmings; some fried tortillas with cherries and cream; and more cocktails that we'd care to admit. It's very on trend, for sure, but it's got the flavour chops to back itself.

Kitchen closed on Mondays.

Before passing the doors at Spurstowe Arms, take a quick look and make sure you’re wearing your Sunday best. Because the Hackneyites who typically frequent this one seem to generally be a) well-dressed and b) pretty damn attractive. If that doesn't deter, or you fancy yourself up to assimilating, you'll find a super cosy, aged tavern with plenty of vintage charm.

A one room joint dominated by a central bar, you'll spot fresh flowers, candles, wonky lights, refurbished mirrors, vintage paintings and art deco posters. It's effortlessly cool, silently saying, 'Oh what, this thing? We just found it’. There are a few ales on tap but nothing out of the ordinary, and the food is pointed towards gastro, with bar food, sharing boards and a couple of mains changing each month.

What this is, though, is either the physical embodiment of a hangover cure or a venue for a group chill, where you can get together either in the walled - and often busy - beer garden out back, or on a candlelit corner table and enjoy a booze-aided commune.
